@{<NOTE>
<HEAD1>Different modes of convergence</HEAD1>
Let <M>(X_n)</M> be a sequence of random variables, and
let <M>X</M> be some random variable. Then there are various
natural ways in which we can have <M>X_n\to X.</M> 
Before going into the details we shall take a look at some of
them informally. 

Suppose that <M>X_n\sim Unif(*(-[[1n]],1+[[1n]])*).</M> Then it
seems only natural to say that <M>X_n\to X</M> where <M>X\sim Unif(0,1).</M>

As yet another example, consider tossing a fair coin
repeatedly. Let <M>X_n = </M>proportion of heads up to
the <M>n</M>-th toss. Then it is seen that <M>X_n\to [[12]].</M> 
 
</NOTE>@}
